### Extension Methods in C#

Extension methods allow you to add new methods to existing types without modifying the original type.

### Creating Extension Methods

```csharp
// Extension methods must be in a static class
public static class StringExtensions
{
    // First parameter with 'this' keyword specifies the type being extended
    public static string Reverse(this string str)
    {
        char[] chars = str.ToCharArray();
        Array.Reverse(chars);
        return new string(chars);
    }

    public static bool IsPalindrome(this string str)
    {
        string reversed = str.Reverse();
        return str.Equals(reversed, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
    }
}

// Usage
string word = "racecar";
Console.WriteLine(word.Reverse());     // "racecar"
Console.WriteLine(word.IsPalindrome()); // True
```

### Extension Method Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Static class | Must be in a static (non-nested, non-generic) class |
| Static method | Must be static |
| `this` keyword | First parameter uses `this` keyword |
| Namespace | Must be imported with `using` |
| Priority | Instance methods take priority over extension methods |

### Common Extension Methods

```csharp
// LINQ extension methods (System.Linq)
var filtered = numbers.Where(n => n > 5);
var projected = items.Select(i => i.Name);

// Common custom extensions
public static bool IsNullOrEmpty(this string str)
    => string.IsNullOrEmpty(str);

public static T? GetValueOrDefault<T>(this Dictionary<string, T> dict, string key)
    => dict.TryGetValue(key, out T? value) ? value : default;

public static bool In<T>(this T item, params T[] items)
    => items.Contains(item);
```

### Extending Interfaces

```csharp
public static class EnumerableExtensions
{
    public static void ForEach<T>(this IEnumerable<T> source, Action<T> action)
    {
        foreach (T item in source)
            action(item);
    }

    public static bool IsEmpty<T>(this IEnumerable<T> source)
        => !source.Any();
}
```

### Fluent API with Extension Methods

```csharp
public static class QueryExtensions
{
    public static IQueryable<T> WhereActive<T>(this IQueryable<T> query)
        where T : IActivatable
        => query.Where(e => e.IsActive);
}
```

### Chaining Extensions

```csharp
string result = "  Hello World  "
    .Trim()
    .Reverse()
    .ToUpper();
```

> **Key Point:** Extension methods enable adding functionality to closed types (including BCL types). They are syntactic sugar - they compile to static method calls. Instance methods always take priority. Use extension methods wisely to avoid cluttering types.

### Extension Method Discovery

```csharp
// Import the namespace where the static class lives
using MyExtensions;  // Now extension methods are available
```

### Extending Value Types

```csharp
public static class IntExtensions
{
    public static bool IsEven(this int value) => value % 2 == 0;
    public static bool IsOdd(this int value) => value % 2 != 0;
    public static int Square(this int value) => value * value;
}

// Usage
int x = 5;
Console.WriteLine(x.IsEven());  // False
Console.WriteLine(x.Square());  // 25
```

### Generic Extension Methods

```csharp
public static T? GetRandomElement<T>(this IEnumerable<T> source)
{
    var list = source.ToList();
    if (list.Count == 0) return default;
    return list[Random.Shared.Next(list.Count)];
}

var rand = new[] { "A", "B", "C" }.GetRandomElement();
```

